1775
01:32:33,128 --> 01:32:35,797
it can ask for access
to the network

1776
01:32:35,797 --> 01:32:38,166
to provide extended
functionality.

1777
01:32:38,166 --> 01:32:40,802
We put those controls
in your hands.

1778
01:32:40,802 --> 01:32:44,572
That's extensions on iOS 8.

1779
01:32:44,572 --> 01:32:51,446
[ Applause ]

1780
01:32:51,446 --> 01:32:55,583
Next up, Touch ID.

1781
01:32:55,583 --> 01:32:58,119
[ Applause ]

1782
01:32:58,119 --> 01:33:02,824
From the moment we
introduced Touch ID,

1783
01:33:02,824 --> 01:33:05,660
developers were excited
about the potential

1784
01:33:05,660 --> 01:33:07,429
and there's no question why,

1785
01:33:07,429 --> 01:33:10,899
Touch ID has been
extremely popular

1786
01:33:10,899 --> 01:33:12,734
and people authenticating
in their devices.

1787
01:33:12,734 --> 01:33:14,703
If you look at passcode usage

1788
01:33:14,703 --> 01:33:17,806
on iOS before Touch
ID was less than half.

1789
01:33:17,806 --> 01:33:23,178
On iPhone 5s 83 percent,
people love using Touch ID.

1790
01:33:23,178 --> 01:33:26,114
And now, third party
apps can take advantage

1791
01:33:26,114 --> 01:33:28,550
of Touch ID as well.

1792
01:33:28,550 --> 01:33:36,424
[ Applause ]

1793
01:33:36,424 --> 01:33:39,227
So Touch ID protects logins
and user data and it works

1794
01:33:39,227 --> 01:33:41,663
by unlocking Keychain items.

1795
01:33:41,663 --> 01:33:44,666
So it identifies successful
fingerprint matches

1796
01:33:44,666 --> 01:33:47,769
but it always keeps the
fingerprint data itself

1797
01:33:47,769 --> 01:33:49,571
completely protected inside

1798
01:33:49,571 --> 01:33:53,074
of the Secure Enclave
in the A7 processor.

1799
01:33:53,074 --> 01:33:55,176
The fingerprint information
is never exposed

1800
01:33:55,176 --> 01:33:58,079
to third party apps or the rest
of the system for that matter.

1801
01:33:58,079 --> 01:34:00,148
It's very secure.

1802
01:34:00,148 --> 01:34:01,282
That's Touch ID.

1803
01:34:01,282 --> 01:34:03,518
Then next, Cameras.

1804
01:34:03,518 --> 01:34:08,690
We're providing Camera APIs
from manual control of exposure,

1805
01:34:08,690 --> 01:34:10,992
white balance and focus.

1806
01:34:10,992 --> 01:34:15,330
And we've enhanced the PhotoKit
API with faster performance,

1807
01:34:15,330 --> 01:34:17,465
the ability not just to
read but also to write

1808
01:34:17,465 --> 01:34:20,401
to the photo library and this
is now your cloud photo library

1809
01:34:20,401 --> 01:34:22,337
and perform non-destructive
edits.

1810
01:34:22,337 --> 01:34:24,906
It's really great.

1811
01:34:24,906 --> 01:34:27,142
Now, we talked about
the great HealthKit API,

1812
01:34:27,142 --> 01:34:31,546
but now we'd also have HomeKit.

1813
01:34:31,546 --> 01:34:38,953
[ Applause ]

1814
01:34:38,953 --> 01:34:42,323
Now, there are a lot of great
home automation devices coming

1815
01:34:42,323 --> 01:34:44,559
on the market these days and
they have companion apps,

1816
01:34:44,559 --> 01:34:48,930
things like lights and
door locks, webcams,

1817
01:34:48,930 --> 01:34:52,400
garage doors, and thermostats.

1818
01:34:52,400 --> 01:34:55,069
But, you know, each of them
have their own application

1819
01:34:55,069 --> 01:34:59,007
and they end up defining
their own network protocol,

1820
01:34:59,007 --> 01:35:01,476
their own security mechanisms.

1821
01:35:01,476 --> 01:35:05,113
Well, we thought we could bring
some rationality to the space.

1822
01:35:05,113 --> 01:35:07,816
We started working
with the leaders

1823
01:35:07,816 --> 01:35:10,285
in home automation devices.

1824
01:35:10,285 --> 01:35:15,123
And we've come up with HomeKit
with a common network protocol

1825
01:35:15,123 --> 01:35:17,425
that has secure pairing
to ensure

1826
01:35:17,425 --> 01:35:20,762
that only your iPhone
can open your garage door

1827
01:35:20,762 --> 01:35:22,630
or unlock your door.

1828
01:35:22,630 --> 01:35:25,767
And in addition to being able
to control individual devices

1829
01:35:25,767 --> 01:35:29,504
in your home, with HomeKit you
can group devices and changes

1830
01:35:29,504 --> 01:35:33,141
in the scenes and then with
Siri integration you can say

1831
01:35:33,141 --> 01:35:35,710
something like, "Get ready
for bed," and be assured

1832
01:35:35,710 --> 01:35:38,379
that your garage door is
closed, your door is locked,

1833
01:35:38,379 --> 01:35:39,681
the thermostat is lower,

1834
01:35:39,681 --> 01:35:43,551
and your lights are
dimmed, that's HomeKit.

1835
01:35:43,551 --> 01:35:51,593
[ Applause ]

1836
01:35:51,593 --> 01:35:53,928
Next, CloudKit.

1837
01:35:53,928 --> 01:35:55,830
So today, if you're a developer

1838
01:35:55,830 --> 01:35:57,532
and you're writing
an application

1839
01:35:57,532 --> 01:36:00,635
and it needs a web component,
well, you end up really having

1840
01:36:00,635 --> 01:36:02,637
to write two apps in one.

1841
01:36:02,637 --> 01:36:05,506
In addition to the writing in
the client side using Xcode

1842
01:36:05,506 --> 01:36:06,841
and our frameworks, you have

1843
01:36:06,841 --> 01:36:08,209
to write the server
side of the app.

1844
01:36:08,209 --> 01:36:11,813
You have to write server side
app logic, you have to deal

1845
01:36:11,813 --> 01:36:14,649
with authentication, asset
storage, database storage,

1846
01:36:14,649 --> 01:36:17,018
search, even push
notifications and then you got

1847
01:36:17,018 --> 01:36:19,287
to pay somebody to host it all.

1848
01:36:19,287 --> 01:36:23,091
Well, now, with CloudKit,
CloudKit takes

1849
01:36:23,091 --> 01:36:25,760
over the cloud part
and provide you

1850
01:36:25,760 --> 01:36:28,363
with a client side
programming model

1851
01:36:28,363 --> 01:36:32,567
that lets you access iCloud
authentication storage,

1852
01:36:32,567 --> 01:36:34,535
search and more.

1853
01:36:34,535 --> 01:36:36,871
And when it comes to paying,

1854
01:36:36,871 --> 01:36:45,747
CloudKit is effectively
free, with limits.

1855
01:36:45,747 --> 01:36:49,651
So, CloudKit scales the
data allocated to your app

1856
01:36:49,651 --> 01:36:53,288
and bandwidth based on the
number of users using your app.

1857
01:36:53,288 --> 01:36:56,958
And this goes all the way up
to granting you free a petabyte

1858
01:36:56,958 --> 01:36:59,427
of assets, 10 terabytes
of database

1859
01:36:59,427 --> 01:37:02,931
and all the bandwidth you
can constructively use.

1860
01:37:02,931 --> 01:37:05,500
That is CloudKit.

1861
01:37:05,500 --> 01:37:13,441
[ Applause ]

1862
01:37:13,441 --> 01:37:16,711
Next, I want to move on to
something huge in the area

1863
01:37:16,711 --> 01:37:23,017
of 3D graphics, and
it's called Metal, so--

1864
01:37:23,017 --> 01:37:24,886
[ Laughter ]

1865
01:37:24,886 --> 01:37:29,357
As you know, OpenGL is
the standards based way

1866
01:37:29,357 --> 01:37:33,494
for high performance 3D graphics
on iOS, giving you access

1867
01:37:33,494 --> 01:37:37,031
to the power of the
A7 processor.

1868
01:37:37,031 --> 01:37:39,500
But increasingly, if you look at
what goes on in the performance

1869
01:37:39,500 --> 01:37:42,470
of the game, in addition to what
the game wants to accomplish,

1870
01:37:42,470 --> 01:37:46,474
OpenGL ends up being a
thick layer of overhead

1871
01:37:46,474 --> 01:37:49,777
between the game
and the hardware.

1872
01:37:49,777 --> 01:37:51,412
Well, now, we have Metal.

1873
01:37:51,412 --> 01:37:54,015
And Metal dramatically reduces

1874
01:37:54,015 --> 01:37:56,684
that overhead giving
the game near bare

1875
01:37:56,684 --> 01:37:59,988
to the metal access
to the power of A7.

1876
01:37:59,988 --> 01:38:05,727
The results are stunning up
to 10x faster draw call rates.

1877
01:38:05,727 --> 01:38:11,466
Now, in addition to these
dramatically reduced overheads,

1878
01:38:11,466 --> 01:38:13,234
you get access not
just to graphics

1879
01:38:13,234 --> 01:38:16,204
but to the compute
power of the GPU,

1880
01:38:16,204 --> 01:38:18,539
and Metal supports
pre-compiled shaders

1881
01:38:18,539 --> 01:38:19,941
and efficient multithreading

1882
01:38:19,941 --> 01:38:23,111
so you can always get the
most out of the processor.

1883
01:38:23,111 --> 01:38:26,514
Now, we've been working
with the leading providers

1884
01:38:26,514 --> 01:38:30,651
of gaming engines
on mobile platforms

1885
01:38:30,651 --> 01:38:33,154
and what they've been able
to accomplish with Metal

1886
01:38:33,154 --> 01:38:37,191
in just a few weeks
is truly stunning.

1887
01:38:37,191 --> 01:38:39,961
Let's start with EA and the
work they've done taking their

1888
01:38:39,961 --> 01:38:47,502
console level title Plants vs.
Zombies and bringing it to iOS.

1889
01:38:47,502 --> 01:38:52,240
They're able to put over 1.3
million triangles on the screen

1890
01:38:52,240 --> 01:38:55,476
at a time and do depth
of motion, effects,

1891
01:38:55,476 --> 01:38:58,713
depth of field effects that they
could never imagine achieving.

1892
01:38:58,713 --> 01:39:02,150
In fact, they're using their
Frostbyte console engine

1893
01:39:02,150 --> 01:39:05,920
that they thought could never
come to mobile and now it can.

1894
01:39:05,920 --> 01:39:08,523
And let's look at Crytek.

1895
01:39:08,523 --> 01:39:13,728
Crytek was able to bring their
console-level geom cache to iOS

1896
01:39:13,728 --> 01:39:14,862
and they were able to get

1897
01:39:14,862 --> 01:39:18,533
up to 4000 draw calls
per frame going here.

1898
01:39:18,533 --> 01:39:20,468
This is up to 10x, the kind

1899
01:39:20,468 --> 01:39:23,704
of performance they
were seeing previously.

1900
01:39:23,704 --> 01:39:29,277
Now, to show you live what
can be done with Metal,

1901
01:39:29,277 --> 01:39:32,346
I'd like to bring up the
founder of Epic Games

